Author

Martin Hsu

Markov Chains

Every day for lunch you have either a sandwich (state 1), a burrito (state 2), or pizza (state 3). Suppose your lunch choices from one day to the next follow a Markov chain with transition matrix

\[ \textbf{P} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0.5 & 0.5 \\ 0.1 & 0.4 & 0.5 \\ 0.2 & 0.3 & 0.5 \end{bmatrix} \]

Suppose today is Monday and consider your upcoming lunches.

  • Monday is day 0, Tuesday is day 1, etc.
  • You start with pizza on day 0 (Monday).
  • Let \(T\) be the first time (day) you have a sandwich. (Note: it is possible for \(T\) to be greater than 4.)
  • Let \(V\) be the number of times (days) you have a burrito this five-day work week.
  • Pizza costs $5, burrito $7, and sandwich $9.
  • Let \(X_n\) be the cost of your lunch on day \(n\).
  • Let \(W=X_0+\cdots+X_4\) be your total lunch cost for this five-day work week.

Write code to setup and run a simulation to investigate the following.

Approximate the marginal distribution, along with the expected value and standard deviation, of each of the following:

1) \(X_4\)

First, letâs simulate one sample path, AKA one 5-day work week of pizzas, burritos and sandwiches:

Code 
# Define state space
state_names <- c(9, 7, 5)
# Define transition matrix
P <- rbind(
  c(0, 0.5, 0.5),
  c(0.1, 0.4, 0.5),
  c(0.2, 0.3, 0.5)
)
# Name the entries of the transition matrix
colnames(P) <- state_names
rownames(P) <- state_names
# Print transition matrix
as.data.frame(P)
Code 
# Set path length
n <- 5
# Set starting distribution
pi_0 <- c(0, 0, 1)
# Simulate a path
path <- numeric(n)
# First select starting state based on starting distribution
path[[1]] <- sample(state_names, 1, prob = pi_0)
# Then until we reach nth entry, we select next state based on transition matrix
for (i in 2:n) {
  path[[i]] <- sample(state_names, 1, prob = P[as.character(path[[i-1]]),])
}
# Print path
path
[1] 5 7 5 9 5

Now, letâs do this multiple times to create a sample of paths:

Code 
# Turn our one-path simulation code into a function
lunch_path <- function(P, state_names, pi_0, n) {
  path <- numeric(n)
  path[[1]] <- sample(state_names, 1, prob = pi_0)
  for (i in 2:n) {
    path[[i]] <- sample(state_names, 1, prob = P[as.character(path[[i-1]]),])
  }
  return(path)
}
Code 
# Specify number of sample paths
reps <- 10000
# Initialize list of paths
samp <- NULL
# Create paths
for (i in 1:reps) {
  samp <- rbind(samp, lunch_path(P, state_names, pi_0, n))
}
# Name Xn's
colnames(samp) <- c("X0", "X1", "X2", "X3", "X4")
samp <- as.data.frame(samp)

Now, we can approximate each of the sample statistics for each of the random variables, starting with \(X_4\).

Letâs define a few helper functions to do that:

Code 
marginal_dist <- function(sample_paths, var) {
  # Get density for each unique value of var
  dist <- sample_paths %>%
    group_by({{ var }}) %>%
    summarise(P = n() / nrow(sample_paths))
  return(dist)
}
Code 
plot_marginal_dist <- function(sample_paths, var) {
  # Get variable name as string - for our graph labels
  varname <- deparse(substitute(var))
  # Plot histogram of marginal distribution
  sample_paths %>%
    ggplot(mapping=aes({{ var }})) +
    geom_histogram(aes(y = ..count.. / sum(..count..))) +
    labs(title = paste("Simulated Marginal Distribution of", varname, "with", nrow(sample_paths), "Paths"),
         x = varname,
         y = "Density") +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
          panel.grid.minor = element_blank())
}

From this distribution, we can infer that on Friday, I am most likely to buy a pizza, and least likely to buy a sandwich.

2) \(T\)

Because T (first sandwich encounter) can be greater than 4, we need to make a special simulation. (All other variables can rely on our \(X_4\) simulation.) We need paths that go beyond 5 steps, at least until we encounter our first sandwich. As a result, rather than stopping at \(X_4\), this new simulation only terminates a path when we finally encounters a sandwich (which is coded by its cost of $9), or when we reach \(X_4\), whichever happens last.

Code 
lunch_path_t <- function(P, state_names, pi_0, terminal_state) {
  # Get initial state
  state <- sample(state_names, 1, prob = pi_0)
  # Initialize index for while loop
  i <- 2
  # Initialize path
  path <- numeric()
  # Set path starting state
  path[[1]] <- state
  # Keep generating new states in the path until we encounter terminal state
  while (!(state == terminal_state)) {
    state <- sample(state_names, 1, prob = P[as.character(path[[i-1]]),])
    path[[i]] <- state
    # Remember to increment
    i = i + 1
  }
  # If there is less than 6 steps, bring it up to 6
  while (i <= 6) {
    state <- sample(state_names, 1, prob = P[as.character(path[[i-1]]),])
    path[[i]] <- state
    # Remember to increment
    i = i + 1
  }
  return(path)
}

Now letâs approximate each of our joint distributions, starting with \(X_4\) and \(X_5\).

Letâs define a few helper functions to do that:

Code 
joint_dist <- function(sample_paths, var1, var2) {
  # Get crosstab of frequencies
  ctab <- sample_paths %>%
    group_by({{ var1 }}, {{ var2 }}) %>%
    summarise(p = n()) %>%
    pivot_wider(names_from = {{ var2 }},
                values_from = p,
                values_fill = 0) %>%
    as.matrix()
  # Name rows
  rownames(ctab) <- ctab[,1]
  # Normalize
  ctab <- as.data.frame(ctab[, -1] / nrow(sample_paths))
  return(ctab)
}
Code 
plot_joint_dist <- function(sample_paths, var1, var2) {
  varname1 <- deparse(substitute(var1))
  varname2 <- deparse(substitute(var2))
  xbins <- sample_paths %>%
    distinct({{ var2 }}) %>%
    count() %>%
    pull
  ybins <- sample_paths %>%
    distinct({{ var1 }}) %>%
    count() %>%
    pull
  
  sample_paths %>%
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = {{ var2 }},
                         y = {{ var1 }},
                         fill = ..count.. / sum(..count..))) +
    geom_bin2d(bins = c(min(xbins, 30), min(ybins, 30))) +
    scale_fill_continuous(type = "viridis") +
    labs(x = varname2,
         y = varname1,
         title = paste("Simulated Joint Distribution of", varname1, "and", varname2, "with", nrow(sample_paths), "Paths"),
         fill = "Density") +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
          panel.grid.minor = element_blank())
}

3)

Approximate the conditional distribution of \(V\) given \(T=4\), along with its (conditional) mean and standard deviation.

Here, I take the approach of generating repetitions until I have 10,000 repetitions where \(T=4\).

Code 
# Initialize list of T values
VT_samp <- NULL
# Create paths
for (i in 1:reps) {
  # First try
  tpath <- lunch_path_t(P, state_names, pi_0, 9)
  tval <- min(which(tpath == 9)) - 1
  # Retry rep until T=4
  while (tval != 4) {
    tpath <- lunch_path_t(P, state_names, pi_0, 9)
    tval <- min(which(tpath == 9)) - 1
  }
  VT_samp <- rbind(VT_samp, 
                  c(tpath[[1]], tpath[[2]], tpath[[3]], tpath[[4]], tpath[[5]], tpath[[6]],
                    tval))
}
colnames(VT_samp) <- c("X0", "X1", "X2", "X3", "X4", "X5", "T")
# Get V
VT_samp <- as.data.frame(VT_samp) %>%
  mutate(V = (X0 == 7) + (X1 == 7) + (X2 == 7) + (X3 == 7) + (X4 == 7)) %>%
  select(X0, X1, X2, X3, X4, V, `T`)
  
# Print some sample paths
head(VT_samp)

We define some more helper functions:

Code 
cond_dist <- function(sample_paths, var, cond, cond_val) {
  # Get density for each unique value of var
  dist <- sample_paths %>%
    filter({{ cond }} == cond_val)
  nreps <- nrow(dist)
  dist <- dist %>%
    group_by({{ var }}) %>%
    summarise(P = n() / nreps)
  return(dist)
}
Code 
plot_cond_dist <- function(sample_paths, var, cond, cond_val) {
  # Get variable name as string - for our graph labels
  varname <- deparse(substitute(var))
  # Plot histogram of marginal distribution
  sample_cond <- sample_paths %>%
    filter({{ cond }} == cond_val)
  sample_cond %>%
    ggplot(mapping=aes({{ var }})) +
    geom_histogram(aes(y = ..count.. / sum(..count..))) +
    labs(title = paste("Simulated Marginal Distribution of", varname, "with", nrow(sample_cond), "Paths"),
         x = varname,
         y = "Density") +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
          panel.grid.minor = element_blank())
}

Conditional Distribution:

Code

Code 
plot_cond_dist(VT_samp, V, `T`, 4)

Noteably, the conditional distribution of \(V\) given \(T=4\) has a range of \([0,3]\) instead of \([0,4]\). Although it is more symmetrical, it is still right skew. These changes indicate that \(V\) may not be independent of \(T\).

Your choice. Choose at least one other joint, conditional, or marginal distribution to investigate. You can work with \(X_n,T,V,W\), but you are also welcome to define other random variables in this context. You can also look at time frames other than a single week.

Letâs define the following new variables:

  • \(V_1=V=\) The number of burritos we see in the first work week, \(X_0,...,X_4\).
  • \(V_2=\) The number of burritos we see in the second work week. \(X_5,...,X_9\).

We want to examine the joint distribution between these two variables.
